Knowing when to rush to the vet — and when to monitor at home — can save your dog's life. Here are five warning signs that mean **go now**.

## 1. Difficulty Breathing

Labored breathing, gasping, blue-tinged gums, or excessive panting at rest are all signs of respiratory distress. This can indicate heart failure, pneumonia, allergic reactions, or airway obstruction.

**What to do:** Don't wait. Head to the nearest emergency vet immediately.

## 2. Sudden Collapse or Inability to Stand

If your dog collapses, can't stand, or seems suddenly disoriented, it could indicate internal bleeding, a cardiac event, a neurological issue, or severe pain.

**What to do:** Keep your dog calm and still. Transport carefully to the vet.

## 3. Bloated or Distended Abdomen

A swollen belly — especially paired with retching without vomiting, restlessness, or drooling — can signal gastric dilatation-volvulus (GDV or "bloat"). This is life-threatening and requires surgery within hours.

**What to do:** This is a true emergency. Minutes matter.

## 4. Severe Bleeding or Trauma

Any wound that won't stop bleeding, visible bone, or trauma from a car accident or fall needs immediate attention — even if your dog seems okay initially. Internal injuries aren't always visible.

**What to do:** Apply gentle pressure to wounds. Transport immediately.

## 5. Seizures Lasting More Than 3 Minutes

A single brief seizure may not be immediately dangerous, but prolonged seizures (status epilepticus) or clusters of seizures can cause brain damage and are a medical emergency.

**What to do:** Don't restrain your dog during a seizure. Time it. If it lasts more than 3 minutes or repeats, get to a vet.

---

## When in Doubt, Call

Most emergency vet clinics have phone lines staffed 24/7. If you're unsure whether something is an emergency, call. They'll help you decide.

And if cost is what's standing between your dog and care — that's exactly the gap The Wolf Project exists to bridge.

